1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,449
As company policy, he said, we feel the best initial training is to start the young fellow,

2
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:10,770
who incidentally is usually a college graduate, as a male boy.

3
00:00:11,120 --> 00:00:18,290
We don't do this, of course, because we feel a fellow needs four years of college to take mail from one office to another.

4
00:00:18,640 --> 00:00:26,050
Our purpose is to give the new fellow maximum exposure to the many varied things which must be done in agency work.

5
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:29,969
After he knows his way around, we give him an assignment.

6
00:00:30,560 --> 00:00:36,530
Now occasionally, even after we've carefully explained why we're starting him out in the mailroom,

7
00:00:36,720 --> 00:00:41,330
a young fellow feels that carrying the mail is belittling and unimportant.

8
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:45,250
When this is the case, we know we've picked the wrong man.

9
00:00:45,439 --> 00:00:52,770
If he doesn't have the vision to see that being a mailboy is a necessary practical step to important assignments,

10
00:00:52,880 --> 00:00:55,890
then he has no future in the agency business.

11
00:00:56,400 --> 00:01:02,610
Remember, executives answer the question, what would he do on that specific level,

12
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:08,050
by first answering the question, what kind of job is he doing where he is now.

13
00:01:08,800 --> 00:01:10,290
Here is some logic.

14
00:01:10,400 --> 00:01:12,050
Sounds straight and easy.

15
00:01:12,159 --> 00:01:15,330
Listen to it a few times before you continue.

16
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:23,090
A person who thinks his job is important receives mental signals on how to do his job better.

17
00:01:23,280 --> 00:01:29,489
And a better job means more promotions, more money, more prestige, more happiness.

18
00:01:31,439 --> 00:01:38,850
We've all noticed how children quickly pick up the attitudes, habits, fears, and preferences of their parents.

19
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:46,130
whether it be food preferences, mannerisms, religious and political views, or any other type of behavior.

20
00:01:46,400 --> 00:01:53,650
The child is a living reflection of how his parents or guardians think, for he learns through imitation.

21
00:01:53,919 --> 00:01:55,570
And so do adults.

22
00:01:55,760 --> 00:02:02,610
People continue to imitate others throughout life, and they imitate their leaders and supervisors.

23
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:06,530
Their thoughts and actions are influenced by these people.

24
00:02:07,679 --> 00:02:09,570
You can check this easily.

25
00:02:09,679 --> 00:02:16,530
Study one of your friends and the person he works for, and note the similarities in thinking and action.

26
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:22,290
Here are some of the ways your friend may imitate his boss or other associate.

27
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:32,130
Slang and word choice, the way he smokes cigarettes, some facial expressions and mannerisms, choice of clothing, and automobile preferences.

28
00:02:32,320 --> 00:02:34,530
There are many, many more, of course.

29
00:02:35,360 --> 00:02:44,050
Another way to note the power of imitation is to observe the attitudes of employees and compare them with those of the chief.

30
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:50,449
When the chief is nervous, tense, worried, his close associates reflect similar attitudes.

31
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:55,729
But when Mr. Chief is on top, feeling good, so are his employees.

32
00:02:56,320 --> 00:02:57,570
The point is this.

33
00:02:57,760 --> 00:03:04,130
The way we think toward our jobs determines how our subordinates think toward their jobs.

34
00:03:04,800 --> 00:03:10,850
The job attitudes of our subordinates are direct reflections of our own job attitudes.

35
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:18,929
It's well to remember that our points of superiority and weakness show up in the behavior of those who report to us,

36
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:23,090
just as a child reflects the attitudes of his parents.

37
00:03:25,040 --> 00:03:30,130
Consider just one characteristic of successful people—enthusiasm.